solutions.content:
This question follows the same pattern as the fibbonaci series.

Let's see how.

For n=1, no of solutions = 1
For n=2, no of solutions = 2
For n=3, no of solutions = 3  [1+2]
For n=4, no of solutions = 5  [2+3]
For n=5, no of solutions = 8  [3+5]
For n=5, no of solutions = 13 [5+8]

As we can see the steps are sum of it's two predecessors. We can apply the same algorithm for getting the $$n^{th}$$ sum of a fibonacci series here.

We store the already calculated values in a vector array to prevent calculating the same step sum again & again. This in face same a lot of time, thus bringing down the time complexity.

``` C++ []
class Solution {
private:
    int climbStairsdp(int n, vector<int>& dp) {
        if (n<2) return 1;
        if (dp[n]) return dp[n];
        else return dp[n] = climbStairsdp(n-1, dp) + climbStairsdp(n-2, dp);
    }
public:
    int climbStairs(int n) {
        vector<int> dp(n+1);
        return climbStairsdp(n, dp);
    }
};
```

